Analysis of Recipes of Dutch Healthy Food Influencers

Wouter van elteren

2022-08-01

Analysis of Recipes of Dutch Healthy Food Influencers on Instagram

As part of my bachelor thesis, I analysed the recipes promoted by Dutch Healthy Food Influencers on Instagram. Healthy food influencers (i.e.social media influencers that whose main content is healthy food) have seen a sharp rise in popularity due to the corona pandemic and healthy lifestyle trend. However, Dutch nutritionists are concerned about the influence healthy food influencers may have on their audiences meal choice and may even be forming a risk to public health (Ditisten verontust, 2021). They state that most Dutch healthy food influencers started as hobby cooks and are not certified dieticians or nutritionists and therefore should not be in a position to advise on healthy eating. This begs the question: how healthy are their recipes?

Additionally, my thesis examined the effect of the healthiness of a recipe on the amount of social media engagement (in the form of likes and comments) it received.

Data Collection

Healthy Food Influencer Sample

Healthy food influencers were selected by monitoring the Top Posts section of the #gezondenrecpten and #gezondeten hashtags on Instagram daily for a period of one month. Those who made the top posts section more than three times during that month were selected. This resulted in a sample of 19 healthy food influencers. The Instagram posts of each healthy food influencer of last month were subsequently examined. Influencers were removed if they did not provide an ingredient list for their recipes, since an ingredient list is required for the analysis, or if they were not of Dutch nationality. Additionally, an arbitrary threshold was set of 10.000 followers as a requirement for inclusion.

These exclusion criteria resulted in a final sample of 10 Dutch healthy food influencers. As an ethical consideration, the names of the healthy food influencer were made secret.

Healthy Recipe Sample

Since influencers become more popular the more followers they have, which results in more likes and comments, only the recipes of the last four months (14 June 2022 14 March 2022) were cross-sectionally manually scraped. This resulted in a sample of 257 recipes. This sample was later further reduced to 248 recipes based on exclusion criteria as stated in appendix B. The id, ingredient list, number of likes, number of comments, and the post type (i.e.video or picture) of the healthy recipe sample was collected and stored in a CSV file.

Operationalising Variables

Healthiness

The explanatory variable in this studys design is the healthiness of a recipe depicted in a healthy food influencers Instagram post. The healthiness was determined via the NutriScore nutrient profile model. This model calculates a healthiness score (lower is healthier) for a recipe based on its calorie, saturated fat, sodium, otein, fibre, and vegetables, nuts, fruits content per 100g. In this study, the healthiness of a recipe is determined by the healthiness score. The NutriScore model gives meaning to the healthiness score by assigning a corresponding label named the NutriScore. The NutriScore goes from A (most healthy) to E (least healthy). The recommendations for the implementation of the NutriScore model state that public health initiatives should encourage the consumption of foods that receive a Nutri-Score of either A or B, while the consumption of foods that receive a Nutri-Score of D or E should be limited (Federale Overheidsdienst Volksgezondheid, Veiligheid van de Voedselketen en Leefmilieu, 2022).

The NutriScore is based on the following table:

Healthiness Score NutriScore
<-1 A
0 - 2 B
3 - 10 C
11 - 18 D
>19 E

The meaning of the NutriScore finds itself in cancer research. A diet that mainly consist of food from a specific NutriScore has a corresponding increased risk of cancer. See the image below where Q1 corresponds to A, Q2 to B, , Q5 to E

The NutriScore model was chosen for three reasons:

  1. It is most relevant to the study, as NutriScore is adopted in the Netherlands and the sample consists of content from Dutch food influencers

  2. Studies that compared European nutrient profiling models found NutriScore to be the most accurate for establishing objective healthiness

  3. NutriScore translates to real-world effects (e.g.increased risk of cancer).

Both the healthiness score and NutriScore were obtained via the recipe_healthiness_analyser python program.

Key takeaways:

  • It seems there is quite the spread in the healthiness of the recipes promoted, depending on the influencer. Definitely not all recipes are healthy!

  • HFI-8 and maybe HFI-9 may actually not be healthy food influencers given their recipes healthiness. They may be leeching off the #gezonderecepten hashtag to reach a bigger audience.

  • There are recipes that have a healthiness score considered as an probable outlier. This can either be due to a measurement error of recipe_healthiness_analyser or they are simple recipes for cheat days.

  • Especially one recipe from HFI-5 has an healthiness score so extremely unhealthy that it is probably due to a measurement error.

Lets first take a good look at the probable outliers. Lets look at their origin and deal with them accordingly.

As previously mentioned, having a diet of mainly food belonging to a certain NutriScore has real-world implications on the probability of receiving cancer. Therefore, it may be more beneficial to focus on what diet these healthy food influencers are promoting. Consequently, we can calculate the mean healthiness score of their recipes, and assign a NutriScore to that. This way, we can understand how healthy, on average, their recipes are.

# Get the mean healthiness score of recipe content per influencer
healthiness_score_inf.mean <- recipes %>%
  group_by(author) %>%
  summarise_at(vars(healthiness_score), list(mean = mean))

# round that healthiness score
healthiness_score_inf.mean$mean <- round(healthiness_score_inf.mean$mean, 1)

# Assign a NutriScore to it
healthiness_score_inf.mean <- healthiness_score_inf.mean %>%
    mutate(nutri_score_label = case_when(
      (between(mean, -10, -1)) ~ "A",
      (between(mean, -1, 2)) ~ "B",
      (between(mean, 2, 10)) ~ "C")
    )

healthiness_score_inf.mean

Going by the recommendations of Federale Overheidsdienst Volksgezondheid, Veiligheid van de Voedselketen en Leefmilieu, two (supposed) Healthy Food Influencers, HFI-8 and HFI-9, would be promoting a diet that cannot be labeled as healthy.

Conclusion

The concerns of Dutch nutritionists are warranted. Some self-oclaimed healthy food influencers fail to promote a healthy diet, and can therefore be considered a public-health risk. In the event a public entity, NGO or company would like to leverage healthy food influencers as instruments for public health initiatives, they should carefully consider the healthiness of the recipe content they are promoting.

Part 2: Influence of Healthiness of recipes on Social media engagement

Contemporary literature suggest that unhealthy food receives more social media engagement (in the form of likes and comments). It therefore may be interesting, given the significant spread in recipe healthiness for some influencers, to see if the same holds true for our sample.

Data exploration

# Histogram likes per influencer
ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(data = recipes, aes(x = likes)) +
  facet_wrap(~ author)

# Histogram comments per influencer
ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(data = recipes, aes(x = comments)) +
  facet_wrap(~ author)

There are some problems here. Basically, there are many different reasons to like or comment on a instagram posts, and some of these reasons are also very dependent on instagrams algorithm (e.g., if they show you a certain post or not). The sample per influencer is far too small to account for all those different reasons, hence the distributions that are plotted.

To still explore the effect of healthiness of likes and comments, we assume the analytical framework in my thesis holds true. Basically, this assumption holds that humans can generally accurately spot the difference in healthiness of recipes due to the evolutionary advances in our brain, even when the healthiness of recipes only differs slightly. Given this assumption, we can test for influence of healthiness of recipes on social media engagement for all influencers, no matter how much their recipe content varies in healthiness.

By doing so, we can do a mixed-effect model in order to explore that influence and still keep the entire sample size.

But first, we want to explore our explanatory variables (comment and like count) some more.

hist(likes)

hist(comments)

Definitely have to transform these.

length(boxplot(likes ~ author)$out)

## [1] 12
length(boxplot(comments ~ author)$out)

## [1] 8

There are some notable outliers here. Instead of deleting those, and further reducing our already limited sample size, we keep them in. If they are also highly influential, we might run a robust mixed effect model instead.

## [1] 0.1741327
# Visualise
hist(likes_log)

hist(comments_sqrt)

Looks much better, although likes is still not normally distributed. Nevertheless, for mixed-effect models, only the residuals have to be normally distributed, so this is not a problem.

Mixed-Effect Model

To know whether there is an association between likes or comments as a function of the healthiness score of a recipe, we must first control for the variation in influencer. To do so, we fit the feature influencer as random effect. Additionally, since our dataset of recipe posts also states whether a recipe was promoted in a video or picture, we can account for this variable as well by fitting it as a fixed effect (binary variables cannot be random effects).

The lmerTest package is used for fitting mixed-effect models since it spits out p-values via Satterthwaites approximation method, which is superior to likelihood ratio tests for small sample sizes.

library(lmerTest)

# First models
likes.lmm <- lmer(likes_log ~ healthiness_score + (1|author), data = recipes)
comments.lmm <- lmer(comments_sqrt ~ healthiness_score + (1|author), data = recipes)
summary(likes.lmm)

For both, p is higher than 0.05. Although the usage of p-values for mixed effect model selection is heavily debated, it paints a clear picture here that there is no association between healthiness score and likes and comments.

We could expand our model: making it more complex by accounting for the effect of the media type of the recipe post (video or media), but that would most likely be beating a dead horse, given the output of the current models.

Conclusion

No association could be found between the healthiness of a recipe and the amount of social media engagement it would receive. Our sample size is most likely too small to explore this interaction. Therefore, drawing any other conclusions from these findings will not be possible.
